		<paragraphs><title> Reading Questions </title>
			<exercise><title> Select the Equilibrium Solutions </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Determine the equilibrium solutions for the autonomous differential equation:
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dt} = y^2 - 4y.
						</me>
						Select all that apply.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement><m>y = 0</m></statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Yes, <m>y = 0</m> is an equilibrium solution. If we set <m>f(y)=0</m>, we have:
								<me>
									y^2 - 4y = 0 \implies y(y - 4) = 0.
								</me>
								This gives us <m>y = 0</m> and <m>y = 4</m>.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement><m>y = 4</m></statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Yes, <m>y = 4</m> is also an equilibrium solution. It is found from the same equation:
								<me>
									y^2 - 4y = 0 \implies y(y - 4) = 0.
								</me>
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement><m>y = 2</m></statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								No, <m>y = 2</m> is not an equilibrium solution. The equilibrium solutions are found by setting <m>f(y) = 0</m>, which gives us only <m>y = 0</m> and <m>y = 4</m>.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement><m>y = -2</m></statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								No, <m>y = -2</m> is not an equilibrium solution. The equilibrium solutions are determined by the roots of the equation <m>y^2 - 4y = 0</m>, which does not include negative values.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement><m>y = 1</m></statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								No, <m>y = 1</m> is not an equilibrium solution. The equilibrium solutions are found by solving <m>f(y) = 0</m>, which gives us only <m>y = 0</m> and <m>y = 4</m>.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</exercise>
		</paragraphs>
	</conclusion>
